    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Weaker Inmates on Death Row</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Marc N Brandt Letter, commenting on August 7 article, says there is no justification for executing people with mental incapacities</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Executing the Mentally Retarded Even as Laws Begin to Shift'' (front page, Aug. 7):</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Executing the Mentally Retarded Even as Laws Begin to Shift'' (front page, Aug. 7):</p>
        <p>For years, Nysarc (formerly the New York State Association for Retarded Children) has fought for equal treatment of people with mental retardation. We have argued for their inclusion in all aspects of society. But in 1995 we successfully argued for their exclusion from New York State's newly enacted death penalty. Some called us hypocritical.</p>
        <p>But death is different. The ultimate penalty requires its own standards. And what standard justifies the horrific spectacle of executing people who cannot comprehend why they will be put to death?</p>
        <p>MARC N. BRANDT  Executive Director, Nysarc  Delmar, N.Y., Aug. 10, 2000</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
